value.value: A delimited region of dense mesenchyme within looser mesenchyme.
A delimited region of dense mesenchyme within looser mesenchyme whose cells are committed to become myoblasts.
A delimited region of dense mesenchyme within looser mesenchyme whose cells are committed to become chondroblasts.
Mesenchyme whose cells are embedded in obvious amounts fo extracellular matrix.
Mesenchymal cells that are migrating.
Multi-tissue mesenchymal structure one of whose parts contains stem cells that can replace other parts.
The collection of structures that form the exxtenal covering of the organism.
A furrow or an incomplete tube.
A raised strip of tissue.
The rigid support system for the body.
That part of the conceptus that will form the organism.
Anlagen are populations of contiguous cells, typically arranged in one plane, that are morphologically indistinct, but that already correspond in extent to a later organ/tissue.
Primordia are populations of contiguous cells that are morphologically distinct and already correspond in extent to a later organ/tissue.
Appendage of an animal used for locomotion or grasping.
Multicellular anatomical structure with largely bona fide boundary that extends outwards from or is part of the organism surface and transduces some sensory stimulus to the nervous system.
A part of the body present only in a specific gender.
A part of the body present only in males.
A part of the body present only in females.
A part of the body present only in hermaphrodites.
A flexible joint between two bones that is made of unossified connective tissue.
The articular cartilage covering of the region of bone within a synoval joint.
Cartilage that may provide the template for an endochondral bone or that may be a disinct entity in the skeleton.
The epithelial membrane between bone ends that forms the lateral borders of the synovial cavity and secretes synovial fluid.
A joint connecting two or more bones with cartilage at the bone ends and a synovial membrane that secretes synovial fluid conecting the bones and sealing the synovial cavity.
A component of the exoskeleton.
The cavity within the body that contains the visceral organs.
Multi-tissue structure one of whose parts contains stem cells that can replace other parts.
An acellular fluid portion of organism substance that is produced by the organism for some non-waste purpose.
Multi-tissue epithelial structure one of whose parts contains stem cells that can replace other parts.

Organ or organ part that is attached to the body of an organism. For example a limb[GO, modified]. An appendage is an external body part, or natural prolongation, that protrudes from an organism's body, such as a vertebrate's limbs.
All the products of the fertilized egg.
The part of the conceptus that may be lost before birth or will be discarded at birth, or when the embryo becomes an independent organism.
An anatomical structure present in the larval form of an animal.
A head-associated surface sense organ.
A membranous structure with more than one cell type, one or more of which secretes mucus, that lines body passages which communicate with the exterior.
An anatomical structure that, as part of its normal physiology, undergoes regeneration. Examples include endometrium and antlers.
A group of neurons that provides a nervous response from a tissue.
A group of neurons that provides a nervous signal to a tissue.
An anatomical entity consisting of a single or a few multinucleated structures.
An roughly circular indentation in a surface.
A roughly circular bulge in a surface.
An epithelium that extends its surface area by peripheral movement.
An epithelial tube that transports blood.
An epithelial tube that transports blood away from the heart.
An epithelial tube that transports blood towards the heart.
Anatomical group whose component structures are arranged in a row.
The sum of all the anlagen and primordia that will develop into a single functional system.
The mesenchymal derivative of a somite that will migrate to surround the neural tube and form vertebrae.
A delimited region of osteoblasts representing the early stages of bone formation.
The bilaminar epithelium formed from the myotome and dermatome.
